  			<div id="item-2750"><p>Wow, that looks wonderful. I&#8217;m currently trying to keep myself from buying a Kitchenaid stand mixer that is amazingly priced on Amazon (and free shipping!). But everyone posting wonderful recipes like this one that should have a mixer aren&#8217;t helping.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m so conflicted!</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<a href="http://www.metakathryn.com"><span class="alias">Kathryn</span></a>
  				<span>on September 13, 2006</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-2751"><p>Amazon does have great prices on appliances and other kitchen ware. They currently have a blender for $39 I have my eye on. I got my mother a stand mixer from them for Christmas last year, one of the artisan ones, in a really pretty red, for a great price, with no tax or shipping, plus a rebate of $25.</p>
<p>For this recipe I used my Cuisinart food processor, but I use the stand mixer whenever I make cookies, cakes, and some breads. If you have the room in your kitchen you won&#8217;t regret it. (You have a Cuisinart, right?)</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">Rebecca</span></span>
  				<span>on September 13, 2006</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-2752"><p>I make this just as Rebecca does as I have the same cookbook with the same ridiculous directions, but I have replaced the rhubarb jam filling with one from Rita Newell, innkeeper at Reading House in Watkins Glen, NY, which is so amazing you may not even get it onto the cookie crust but end up eating it with a spoon at the counter. Warm it&#8217;s a compote, chilled it&#8217;s jam. Either way, it&#8217;s fabulous.</p>
Rhubarb-Ginger Jam (makes about 3 cups)
<p>2 lbs rhubarb, washed, trimmed, &amp; cut crosswise into 1&quot; pieces</p>
<p>2 to 2 1/2 cups sugar, to your taste</p>
<p>1/2 cup crystallized ginger</p>
<p>zest of 1 lemon</p>
<p>Combine the ingredients in a medium, heavy-bottomed saucepan over medium high heat. Bring to a boil, stirring till the sugar has dissolved.  Reduce heat to medium &amp; cook at least 20 min. (it may take as long as 40 min.), stirring often, till the mixture thickens &amp; mounds on a spoon.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">April</span></span>
  				<span>on September 13, 2006</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-2753"><p>Yum, that jam does sound good, April! I do replace the water in the Dorie Greenspan recipe with orange juice, but otherwise follow it as written, but I love the sound of the ginger in yours.</p>
<p>But reading your comment reminded me that I must have a container of rhubarb jam lurking in the back of the fridge somewhere, since you only need about half of what you make for the shortbread. I should unearth and use it before it&#8217;s covered with green fuzz&#8230;</p></div>
